{"key":"post-11575389","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11575389</id>\n<content>Just about any grain you can find that isn't too starchy will work.&amp;nbsp; You'll just have to experiment with what you can find locally.&amp;nbsp; If it's too starchy, the grains will all stick together and be hard for the mycelium to colonize and also to break up later.&amp;nbsp; Rye berries are the grain of choice because they aren't starchy at all, thus the grains remain loose.&amp;nbsp; Too bad you can't get it there.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11575410</next>\n<prev>11575377</prev>\n<first>11575377</first>\n<last>11575410</last>\n<when>1259852123</when>\n<utime>12/03/09 04:55 PM</utime>\n</post>"}